Please translate each line literally into English.
103 Volser Virgilio a me queste parole 104 con viso che, tacendo, disse ‘Taci’; 105 ma non può tutto la virtù che vuole;
106 ché riso e pianto son tanto seguaci 107 a la passion di che ciascun si spicca, 108 che men seguon voler ne’ più veraci.

query.result:
103 Virgil turned to me these words
104 with a face that, being silent, said ‘Be silent’;
105 but not everything can virtue do as it wishes;

106 because laughter and weeping are so followers
107 of the passion with which each one distinguishes himself,
108 that they follow will no more or less truthfully.

query.prompt:
Please translate each line literally into English.
109 Io pur sorrisi come l’uom ch’ammicca; 110 per che l’ombra si tacque, e riguardommi 111 ne li occhi ove ’l sembiante più si ficca;
112 e «Se tanto labore in bene assommi», 113 disse, «perché la tua faccia testeso 114 un lampeggiar di riso dimostrommi?».

query.result:
109 I also smiled like the man who winks;
110 for which the shadow became silent, and looked at me
111 in the eyes where the appearance most fixes itself;

112 and “If so much labor sums up in good,”
113 he said, “why did your face extended
114 a flashing of laughter demonstrate to me?”

121 Whence I: “Perhaps you marvel,
122 ancient spirit, at the laughter that I made;
123 but more of admiration I wish you to take.”
